# [LSR](../wg/lsr.html)

## Summary
The LSR (Link State Routing) Working Group met to discuss the status of active drafts, updates to the YANG data models, and progress on flooding reduction mechanisms. Key highlights include the publication of several RFCs related to Segment Routing, progress on OSPF Transport Instance and SRv6 YANG models through the IESG, and technical updates to L2 bundle member advertisements and distributed flooding reduction algorithms.

## Key Discussion Points

### Working Group Status and IESG Progress
*   **RFC Publications:** Several data models for OSPF and IS-IS Segment Routing have been published since IETF 124. The Anycast Property Advertisement is currently in the RFC Editor Queue.
*   **IESG Status:** 
    *   [draft-ietf-lsr-ospf-transport-instance](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-lsr-ospf-transport-instance/) has cleared its discussion points and is moving toward the RFC Editor Queue.
    *   [draft-ietf-lsr-ospf-srv6-yang](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-lsr-ospf-srv6-yang/) and [draft-ietf-lsr-isis-srv6-yang](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-lsr-isis-srv6-yang/) are pending AD evaluation by Gunter Van de Velde.
*   **Flooding Reduction Track:** There was a discussion regarding the status of [draft-ietf-lsr-flood-reduction-arch](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-lsr-flood-reduction-arch/). Tony Li expressed that the authors are flexible regarding the "Experimental" vs. "Informational" track. AD Gunter Van de Velde noted that the IESG is currently refining the definition of "Experimental" documents (requiring clear start/end dates and targets), but the document will proceed regardless of the specific label.

### [02-Advertisement of Remote Interface Identifiers for Layer 2 Bundle Members](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-lsr-5-advertisement-of-remote-interface-identifiers-for-layer-2-bundle-members-00)
**Presenter: Li Yan**
*   **Draft:** [draft-ietf-lsr-l2-bundle-member-remote-id](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-lsr-l2-bundle-member-remote-id/)
*   **Update:** The draft now clarifies use cases for TE and bi-directional path computation. It improves the BGP-LS specification by referencing RFC 9086 and completes security considerations.
*   **Acquisition:** Remote IDs are acquired via L2 protocols (LACP or LLDP Port ID TLV).
*   **Discussion:** Jeff Tantsura inquired about using BFD for LAGs as a discovery mechanism. The authors and chairs (AC Lindem) clarified that while BFD is a possibility, the specific discovery mechanism is out of scope for the IGP advertisement draft, though suggestions can be discussed offline.
*   **Status:** The authors believe the draft is mature and ready for Working Group Last Call (WGLC).

### [03-LSR_YANG_Update](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-lsr-03-lsr-yang-update-00)
**Presenter: Yingzhen Qu**
*   **Strategy:** The WG is moving toward using IANA-maintained modules for registries (e.g., metric types, MSD types). This allows for new extensions without requiring constant updates to the base YANG models.
*   **Drafts:**
    *   [draft-ietf-lsr-ospf-yang-augmentation-v1](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-lsr-ospf-yang-augmentation-v1/) and [draft-ietf-lsr-isis-yang-augmentation-v1](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-lsr-isis-yang-augmentation-v1/) are being streamlined, with Flex Algo moved to separate modules to expedite publication.
    *   [draft-ietf-lsr-isis-pics-yang](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-lsr-isis-pics-yang/) (along with L2 member attributes and SR MPLS PICS) is ready for further review, particularly from service providers.

### [flood reduction update measurements](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-lsr-flood-reduction-update-measurements-00)
**Presenter: Tony Przygienda**
*   **Draft:** [draft-ietf-lsr-distoptflood](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-lsr-distoptflood/)
*   **Technical Updates:** Switched to Fletcher 16 for fragment hashing for better entropy and standardized implementation.
*   **Implementation Status:** A second full implementation has been completed in Rust (Holo stack) by Renato Westphal. Interoperability was successfully tested without CSNPs (Complete Sequence Number Packets) to verify algorithm correctness under stress.
*   **Measurement Results:** Testing focused on the "worst-case" scenario (massive link flapping).
    *   **CPU:** Shows approximately 20% higher CPU consumption during extreme flapping due to cache trashing, but negligible overhead on stable topologies.
    *   **Convergence:** The database synchronizes faster even under heavy load compared to standard flooding.
*   **Discussion:** AC Lindem noted that while CPU usage increases in the worst case, the gain in convergence speed is the primary benefit. Tony Przygienda emphasized that for stable topologies, the gain is significant with zero CPU penalty.

## Decisions and Action Items
*   **L2 Bundle Draft:** The chairs will consider a Working Group Last Call for [draft-ietf-lsr-l2-bundle-member-remote-id](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-lsr-l2-bundle-member-remote-id/) following the meeting.
*   **Code Points:** The authors of [draft-ietf-lsr-distoptflood](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-lsr-distoptflood/) need to request official code points for the algorithms and Router Capability TLVs to facilitate further interoperability testing.
*   **Milestones:** Chairs to update WG milestones upon adoption of new documents to satisfy IESG requirements.

